 1. System Architecture Diagram
 Overview
The Tree Planting and Tracking App follows a 3-tier architecture typical of Django web applications:
Presentation Layer (Frontend/UI) – HTML, CSS, Bootstrap
Application Layer (Backend/Logic) – Python (Django Framework)
Data Layer (Database) – SQLite
Below is the flow of data and system interactions.

 Architecture Flow
 ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
 │                        User Interface                        │
 │  (HTML, CSS, Bootstrap)                                      │
 │  - Registration/Login Forms                                  │
 │  - Dashboard & Leaderboard                                   │
 │  - Add Tree Form & Reports                                   │
 └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    │
                    ▼
 ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
 │                  Django Backend (Application Layer)          │
 │  - URL Routing (urls.py)                                     │
 │  - Views & Controllers (views.py)                            │
 │  - Business Logic (add tree, compute CO₂, leaderboard)       │
 │  - Authentication (login/logout/register)                    │
 │  - Admin Panel Management                                    │
 └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    │
                    ▼
 ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
 │                      Database Layer (SQLite)                 │
 │  - Stores User data (auth_user)                              │
 │  - Stores Tree records (Tree table)                          │
 │  - Stores Species info & CO₂ absorption data (Species table) │
 └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    │
                    ▼
 ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
 │                       GitHub Repository                      │
 │  - Version control for source code                            │
 │  - Collaboration & deployment tracking                        │
 └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
 Data Flow Summary
The user accesses the web interface (frontend).
Requests (HTTP GET/POST) are sent to Django views via URLs.
Django processes the request (logic, validation, calculations).
Data is retrieved or updated in the SQLite database.
The backend sends processed data to the frontend to display dashboards, reports, or leaderboards.

 2. Database Design (ERD – Entity Relationship Diagram)
 Main Entities
User – represents individuals who register and log in.
Tree – represents trees planted by users.
Species – stores data about tree species (optional but useful for CO₂ estimates).

 ERD Structure (Text-Based Representation)
+--------------------+
|      User          |
+--------------------+
| user_id (PK)       |
| username           |
| email              |
| password           |
| date_joined        |
+--------------------+
          |
          | 1---∞
          |
+--------------------+
|       Tree         |
+--------------------+
| tree_id (PK)       |
| user_id (FK)       → User.user_id
| species_id (FK)    → Species.species_id
| species_name       |
| location           |
| date_planted       |
| photo              |
| co2_absorption     |
+--------------------+

 Relationships Explained
User → Tree = One-to-Many
Each user can plant multiple trees, but each tree is associated with one user.
Species → Tree = One-to-Many
Each tree belongs to one species, but a species can be linked to many tree entries.

 Django Model Representation
Here’s how the above ERD maps to Django models:
from django.db import models
from django.contrib.auth.models import User

class Species(models.Model):
    name = models.CharField(max_length=100)
    avg_co2_absorption = models.FloatField(help_text="Average CO2 absorbed per year (kg)")
    description = models.TextField(blank=True)

    def __str__(self):
        return self.name


class Tree(models.Model):
    user = models.ForeignKey(User, on_delete=models.CASCADE)
    species = models.ForeignKey(Species, on_delete=models.SET_NULL, null=True, blank=True)
    species_name = models.CharField(max_length=100)
    location = models.CharField(max_length=200)
    date_planted = models.DateField()
    photo = models.ImageField(upload_to='tree_photos/', blank=True, null=True)
    co2_absorption = models.FloatField(default=0.0)

    def __str__(self):
        return f"{self.species_name} - {self.user.username}"

 3. How the Architecture and Database Work Together
When a user logs in, Django authenticates them through the User model.
When they add a new tree, data is stored in the Tree table linked to that user.
If species data exists, the app retrieves the average CO₂ value from the Species table.
The backend computes total CO₂ absorbed by summing the user’s trees.
The frontend dashboard (HTML + Bootstrap) displays this information visually (charts, cards, and leaderboards).
